While rhizobial colonization promotes legume growth and vigor, this improved host quality can also increase susceptibility to belowground (
 Quinn and Hower, 1986; 
 Gerard, 2001; 
 Johnson and McNicol, 2010) and aboveground insect herbivores (
 Dean et al., 2009, 
 2014; 
 Kempel et al., 2009; 
 Katayama et al., 2010; 
 Whitaker et al., 2014). Beneficial effects of rhizobia on herbivores most likely arise through increased provision of nitrogen, which is frequently limiting in insect herbivore diets (
 Mattson, 1980). Increased provision of nitrogen may, however, allow plants to invest in plant defenses with negative impacts on herbivores (
 Pineda et al., 2010; 
 Brunner et al., 2015). While Si supplementation usually increases plant resistance to herbivores (mainly reported in the Poaecae; 
 Reynolds et al., 2009), it may also indirectly increase susceptibility to herbivores via increases in legume growth and nutritional quality (
 Johnson et al., 2017).
